Prologue
"Please!" pleaded Queen Eirwen. "Don't send her away! She's just a child!" King of Ice looked down at his wife from his throne, his royal advisor standing beside him. She had given birth to a daughter. The thought made him frown.
The little girl resembled her mother very much: pale blue eyes, white hair streaked with blue strands. King of Ice thought that having a daughter would make him seem weak. After all, he had only had sons up until now.
"Your only options are to kill your child or to send her back into the wild. This is her punishment for your bad behavior, Eirwen." He spat out her name as if it were poison. He always did.
Frostwell had not always been a single kingdom. It had been split into two, the North and the South. In the North, a non-magical kingdom. In the South, a kingdom filled with fantastic representations of power. Because of the North's greed, the two kingdoms had torn each other apart in an endless war, until the South proposed a truce.
The South was cornered, and its royal family would have done anything to stop the bloodshed. They proposed that their only princess become queen of the North and bear a son destined to be the future king. Afterwards, the South would have allied with the North to form a single kingdom. The North had accepted, and Princess Eirwen married Prince Akull.
"Please, my highness, in exchange for the life of my child, do whatever you wish with me—imprison me, banish me, or even kill me," pleaded Queen Eirwen, holding her child tightly in her arms.
The King of Ice looked down at his wife, disgust in his eyes. Perhaps, perhaps he would have pity on her. The one with whom he had lived for twenty-two years, who had always taken care of him in his darkest hours, who had given birth to his sons.
"So be it, the child will live in the palace," he began, drawing a sigh of relief from his wife. "However," he added, "you will be executed."
The advisor and Queen Eirwen herself exchanged a horrified look. She gently lowered her eyes. "Yes, Your Highness," she said, bowing.
The King of Ice ordered the royal advisor to take the child into one of Eirwen's vacant apartments. Once this was done, he commanded the guards to lead Eirwen to the execution site, where all the town's inhabitants could witness the spectacle.
As the guards escorted her to the site, the residents cried out in indignation upon seeing their only queen, the kindest among them, about to be killed. Some people were crying, others were shouting and trying to attack the guards, while still others were wondering what was happening, but all were outraged.
"Free her!"
"Why are they doing that to him?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden gallows, the most feared person in the kingdom made their entrance. The wielder of fire. The former queen Eirwen was about to be burned alive. No one deserved such a death, not even criminals. It was the cruelest punishment in Frostfell.
Eirwen was tied to the gallows, and the king began to explain how the queen had betrayed them all. The people of Frostfell refused to believe him and never accepted his words. Then, the wielder of fire set the gallows ablaze, and a single tear rolled down the ex-queen's cheek.
"Survive, Kari." This was the end of Queen Eirwen's reign.
Silence in the hallways
Tap, tap, tap. These were the only sounds coming from the farthest room on the left side of the southern wing of the still-frozen palace. The attendants who passed by always wondered what was inside that room, frightened by whatever might be lurking within. The servants' rumors echoed through the corridors. It was believed that the late queen of Ice, Eirwen, was in that room, waiting to be set free.
"I couldn't be more wrong," thought Ivory as he walked toward the south wing, while the attendants went back and forth, murmuring among themselves. They have no idea at all what is in this room.
Of course, these rumors also applied to them, because they were the only person allowed to enter the room.
Knock knock. "Miss Kari, are you there?" murmured Ivory to the finely decorated door, covered in snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
Iel wondered if she would invite iel in, unlike the other times when iel had asked. I still have bruises from the previous time. Ivory chuckled at the memory. Kari had thrown a book at iel's shoulder, but when she realized who it was, she immediately apologized.
A single knock comes from inside, which seemed to mean that she was there, but after all, where else could she have been?
"Can I come in?" asked Ivory, remembering the time iel had done so without asking for permission.
A knock echoed from inside. It seemed to want to say yes. Ivory shivered, from the cold, but also because of the noise. It was strange for Ivory to hear noise coming from a room supposed to be empty, even though iel had entered this room for years.
"I'm here," said Ivory, gently opening the door. The scene inside the room was unusual by normal standards, but not unexpected. There were papers everywhere. Books were scattered, the desk was broken, and a multitude of ice statuettes were strewn about. The room had no windows and almost no light. It was also colder than the rest of the palace (and that was saying something). A snowstorm seemed to have descended inside.
The girl who was there was curled up in bed, wrapped in her comforter, reading one of her notebooks. A small lantern illuminated the space.
"Which notebook are you talking about?" Ivory asked as she sat down next to Kari on her bed.
